{"id":"421f41ee-870c-4e1d-920b-857019dba26e","userId":"e8f217b2-1fcc-414b-848e-ba2547929ee4","role":"assistant","content":"I'm not a medical professional, and I can't prescribe or recommend specific medications for depression. However, I can provide you with some general information about common types of antidepressant medications that are often used to treat depression.\n\nThere are several classes of antidepressant medications, including:\n\n* Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitors (SSRIs): These medications work by increasing the levels of serotonin in the brain and are often used to treat depression, anxiety, and other mental health conditions. Examples of SSRIs include fluoxetine (Prozac), sertraline (Zoloft), and paroxetine (Paxil).\n* Serotonin-Norepinephrine Reuptake Inhibitors (SNRIs): These medications work by increasing the levels of both serotonin and norepinephrine in the brain. Examples of SNRIs include venlafaxine (Effexor) and duloxetine (Cymbalta).\n* Tricyclic Antidepressants (TCAs): These medications work by increasing the levels of serotonin and norepinephrine in the brain, but they can have more side effects than SSRIs and SNRIs. Examples of TCAs include amitriptyline (Elavil) and imipramine (Tofranil).\n* Monoamine Oxidase Inhibitors (MAOIs): These medications work by increasing the levels of serotonin, norepinephrine, and dopamine in the brain. Examples of MAOIs include phenelzine (Nardil) and tranylcypromine (Parnate).\n\nIt's essential to consult with a mental health professional, such as a psychiatrist or a primary care physician, to determine the best course of treatment for your depression. They can help you develop a treatment plan that includes medication, therapy, or a combination of both.\n\nRemember, medication is just one part of treating depression. It's also important to make lifestyle changes, such as getting","createdAt":"2026-05-15T15:44:26.643Z","_id":"5ILk2p54WmHJ5Wyw"}
